Date: 21 Aug 2007
Source: The Leaf Chronicle [edited]
<http://www.theleafchronicle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070821/NEWS01/708210323>

Deadly virus attacks deer: Drought contributes to
spread of 'epizootic hemorrhagic disease'
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
A number of white-tailed deer have been found
dead near ponds and streams across the region,
and state wildlife officials suspect that the
animals have died of viral disease spread by biting flies.
"We have responded to more than 30 dead deer
reports in the county over the past several weeks
and there are probably many more that have not
been reported," said Montgomery County Wildlife
Officer Jereme Odom. "Laboratory tests are being
conducted to determine the cause of the deaths,
but we suspect that it is hemorrhagic disease
which occurs periodically across the state."
Odom's comments were confirmed by Lucky Pittman,
head of pathology at the Murray State University
Breathitt Veterinary Center in Hopkinsville, KY.
"There is a widespread outbreak of epizootic
hemorrhagic disease this year [2007] that is
affecting white-tailed deer in Kentucky,
Tennessee and Indiana," Pittman said. "Outbreaks
of the disease occur every 2 to 3 years, but this
year is especially severe because of the heat and drought conditions."
Hemorrhagic disease is the most important of the
infectious diseases in white-tailed deer,
according to the Southeast Cooperative Wildlife
Disease Study at the University of Georgia. It is
a viral disease closely related to the bluetongue
virus, and is spread by biting flies. The flies,
also known as sand gnats, sand flies or
no-see-ums, are most abundant from mid-August to
late October, and they usually disappear with the
first hard freeze of the fall season.
The disease problem is compounded this year
[2007] by the record heat and drought conditions.
Water sources are drying up and deer and other
animals are concentrated around available water
sources where they are more likely to come into contact with the disease.
Hemorrhagic disease causes excessive hemorrhaging
and deterioration of blood vessels in the vital
organs of infected animals. Most deer that die of
the disease are found near water because they
develop high fevers and seek water to cool their
bodies. An outbreak of hemorrhagic disease can
kill up to 25 percent of the deer in an outbreak
area, but the mortality can be much higher in some instances.
To date, there has not been an instance where an
entire deer population has been wiped out by the
disease. Past outbreaks of the disease have also
shown up in some cattle and sheep. The deer
infection means that infected flies are present
in the vicinity, and both deer and livestock are
at risk. Once virus activity begins, both deer
and livestock serve to fuel the outbreak, but the
spread of the disease from deer to livestock, or
vice versa, has not been proven.
Livestock owners who suspect hemorrhagic or
bluetongue disease infections in their herds
should seek veterinary assistance to obtain
diagnostic confirmation of the diseases.
The white-tailed deer population of Montgomery
County probably exceeds 20 000 animals. A severe
outbreak of the disease could kill large numbers
of deer, and that may have an impact on the deer
hunting season that opens 22 Sep 2007. Otherwise,
the disease poses no threat to human health, but
hunters should not consume venison from visibly sick deer.
[Byline: Owen Schroeder]
