<http://www.pennlive.com/sports/patriotnews/index.ssf?/base/sports/1187661318226500.xml&coll=1>

Disease suspected in deaths of 50 deer
-------------------------------------------
More than 50 white-tailed deer have been found
dead in southwestern Pennsylvania, suspected
victims of an insect-borne disease known as
epizootic hemorrhagic disease, according to the Pennsylvania Game Commission.
The agency on Monday revealed that samples from 4
of the deer found dead in the impact area in
Greene and Washington counties last week [13-17
Aug 2007] were sent to the Southeastern
Cooperative Wildlife Disease Study at the
University of Georgia and Penn State University
Animal Diagnostics Laboratory. Commission
spokesman Jerry Feaser said test results are expected within the next 2 weeks.
Meanwhile, commission wildlife conservation
officers are collecting information about other
dead deer being found and seeking additional reports.
"We're soliciting input from residents who may be
aware of the die-off but just haven't been asked about it yet," said Feaser.
Reports of dead deer in the impact area were
first received by the commission the week of Aug. 6.
According to Feaser, public release of the
information was delayed until Monday [20 Aug
2007, while the commission confirmed information about the situation.
"It's not like we're hiding anything," he said.
"We had to get all our ducks in order, to make sure we knew what was going on."
The commission has received no reports of
apparent kills in parts of Pennsylvania outside
the 2 southwestern counties, where EHD previously
was confirmed to have killed 70 or more deer in 2002.
However, Feaser noted, "we are hearing suspicions
in other states outside the usual range of EHD."
[Byline: Marcus Schneck]
