Date: 20 Aug 2007
Source WVVA.com [edited]
<http://www.wvva.com/News/index.php?ID=15833>

Deer Deaths Could Be From Insects
--------------------------------------
Wildlife officials say the deaths of more than 50
deer in southwestern Pennsylvania could be from
an insect-borne virus. The state Game Commission
is investigating the deaths of dozens of
white-tailed deer in Greene and Washington
counties since the start of the month [August
2007]. Greene County borders several northern West Virginia counties.
Spokesman Jerry Feaser says officials think the
deer died of EHD (epizootic hemorrhagic disease).
The deer had blueish tongues and reddened lungs.
EHD is a common, seasonal virus among
white-tailed deer, contracted by the bite of
insects called biting midges. EHD cannot be
spread through contact and is not passed from deer to deer.
West Virginia Division of Natural Resources
biologists have found several dead deer, and have
sent samples for testing. EHD was found in the
same vicinity in 2002. That year, the virus was
also confirmed in Maryland, Ohio, Virginia and Wisconsin.
--
